#Text=I.
#Text=RELUCTANCE .
#Text=I.
#Text=Neither life nor the lawn-tennis club was so full at Natterley that the news of Harry Sterling 's return had not some importance .
#Text=He came back , moreover , to assume a position very different from his old one .
#Text=He had left Harrow now , departing in the sweet aroma of a long score against Eton at Lord 's , and was to go up to Oxford in October .

#Text=Now between a schoolboy and a University man there is a gulf , indicated unmistakably by the cigarette which adorned Harry 's mouth as he walked down the street with a newly acquiescent father , and thoroughly realized by his old playmates .

#Text=The young men greeted him as an equal , the boys grudgingly accepted his superiority , and the girls received him much as though they had never met him before in their lives and were pressingly in need of an introduction .

#Text=These features of his reappearance amused Mrs. Mortimer ; she recollected him as an untidy , shy , pretty boy ; but mind , working on matter , had so transformed him that she was doubtful enough about him to ask her husband if that were really Harry Sterling .

#Text=Mr. Mortimer , mopping his bald head after one of his energetic failures at lawn tennis , grunted assent , and remarked that a few years more would see a like development in their elder son , a remark which bordered on absurdity ; for Johnny was but eight , and ten years are not a few years to a lady of twenty-eight , whatever they may seem to a man of forty-four .
#Text=Presently Harry , shaking himself free from an entangling group of the Vicarage girls , joined his father , and the two came across to Mrs. Mortimer .
#Text=She was a favorite of old Sterling 's , and he was proud to present his handsome son to her .
#Text=She listened graciously to his jocosities , stealing a glance at Harry when his father called him " a good boy . "
#Text=Harry blushed and assumed an air of indifference , tossing his hair back from his smooth forehead , and swinging his racket carelessly in his hand .
#Text=The lady addressed some words of patronizing kindness to him , seeking to put him at his ease .

#Text=She seemed to succeed to some extent , for he let his father and her husband go off together , and sat down by her on the bench , regardless of the fact that the Vicarage girls were waiting for him to make a fourth .
#Text=He said nothing , and Mrs. Mortimer looked at him from under her long lashes ; in so doing she discovered that he was looking at her .
#Text=" Are n't you going to play any more , Mr. Sterling ? " she asked .
#Text=" Why are n't you playing ? " he rejoined .
#Text=" My husband says I play too badly . "
#Text=" Oh , play with me !

#Text= Then you must be very good . "

column1: #Text=" Well , no one can play a hang here , you know .

#Text= You forget my weight of years . "

column1: #Text=He opened his blue eyes a little , and laughed .
#Text=He was , in fact , astonished to find that she was quite a young woman .
#Text=Remembering old Mortimer and the babies , he had thought of her as full middle-aged .
#Text=But she was not ; nor had she that likeness to a suet pudding , which his newborn critical faculty cruelly detected in his old friends , the Vicarage girls .

#Text=There was one of them -- Maudie -- with whom he had flirted in his holidays ; he wondered at that , especially when a relentless memory told him that Mrs. Mortimer must have been at the parties where the thing went on .
#Text=He felt very much older , so much older that Mrs. Mortimer became at once a contemporary .
#Text=Why , then , should she begin , as she now did , to talk to him , in quasi maternal fashion , about his prospects ?
#Text=Men do n't have prospects , or , anyhow , are spared questionings thereon .
#Text=Either from impatience of this topic , or because , after all , tennis was not to be neglected , he left her , and she sat alone for a little while , watching him play .
#Text=She was glad that she had not played ; she could not have rivaled the activity of the Vicarage girls .
#Text=She got up and joined Mrs. Sterling , who was presiding over the club teapot .
#Text=The good lady expected compliments on her son , but for some reason Mrs. Mortimer gave her none .
#Text=Very soon , indeed , she took Johnnie away with her , leaving her husband to follow at his leisure .
#Text=In comparing Maudie Sinclair to a suet pudding , Harry had looked at the dark side of the matter .
#Text=The suggestion , though indisputable , was only occasionally obtrusive , and as a rule hushed almost to silence by the pleasant good nature which redeemed shapeless features .
#Text=Mrs. Mortimer had always liked Maudie , who ran in and out of her house continually , and had made of herself a vice-mother to the little children .

#Text=The very next day she came , and , in the intervals of playing cricket with Johnnie , took occasion to inform Mrs. Mortimer that in her opinion Harry Sterling was by no means improved by his new status and dignity .
#Text=She went so far as to use the term " stuck-up . "
#Text=" He did n't use to be like that , " she said , shaking her head ; " he used to be very jolly . "
#Text=Mrs. Mortimer was relieved to note an entire absence of romance either in the regretted past or the condemned present .

#Text=Maudie mourned a friend spoiled , not an admirer lost ; the tone of her criticisms left no doubt of it , and Mrs. Mortimer , with a laugh , announced her intention of asking the Sterlings to dinner and having Maudie to meet them .
#Text=" You will be able to make it up then , " said she .
